Table \ref{tab:CravingTable} shows that the strong valence effect (pro- > anti-alcohol) on alcohol craving replicates across all three studies. Furthermore, in Study 2, we tested the specificity of our results, that is whether our stimuli specifically manipulated alcohol craving as opposed to the general urge to consume beverages. We found a significant interaction between valence and cue type (whether participants rated their urge to consume an alcoholic or non-alcoholic beverage in a given trial). Compared to anti-alcohol messaging, pro-alcohol messaging selectively increased craving for alcoholic beverages and decreased craving for non-alcoholic beverages Table \ref{tab:CravingTable}, Figure ~\ref{fig:cravingPlots}B. 

Main effects derived using \textit{emmeans} reveal no main effects of source across all three studies (Study 1a: $\Sexpr{pc_source1a}$, Study 1b: $\Sexpr{pc_source1b}$, Study 2: $\Sexpr{pc_source2}$) and Table \ref{tab:CravingTable} shows no evidence of interactions between source and valence. 

\subsubsection{Drinking habits and message receptivity}

A possible explanation for the ineffectiveness of anti-alcohol (vs. non-alcoholic) messages is that anti-alcohol messages generally target high risk (binge) drinkers and may not resonate with low risk drinkers. Yet, an additional multi-level regression model fit to Study 1b data (Figure \ref{fig:cravingPlots}C, Supplementary Table 5) shows that those who reported higher binge drinking frequency, on average, reported higher alcohol craving and a higher sensitivity to pro-alcohol (vs. non-alcoholic), but not to anti-alcohol messages. 

\subsection{RQ2: Mechanisms}

Next, we examined the extent to which the different message types succeeded in engaging the two mechanisms (emotional responses and familiarity) and differences between message types in the extent to which each mechanism was coupled with alcohol craving. 

